c}}|'''41%'''\n| 15%{{efn|\"It depends on who the Democratic candidate is\" with 15%}}\n|}\n\n;with Generic Democrat in Maine's 2nd Congressional District\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;text-align:center;\"\n|- valign=bottom style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n! Poll source\n! Date(s)<br>administered\n! Sample<br>size{{efn|name=key}}\n! Margin<br>{{nowrap|of error}}\n! Donald<br>Trump (R)\n! Generic<br>Democrat (D)\n! Undecided\n|-\n| [https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1J_sj0VbK1zPUcErKBWIvCc5d6wFvwhKr_zageM2-I_I/edit#gid=457256029 Colby College]\n| Feb 10-13, 2020\n| 1,008 (LV)\n| \u00b1&nbsp;3.1%\n| {{party shading/Republican}}|'''41%'''\n| 34%\n| 14%{{efn|\"It depends on who the Democratic candidate is\" with 14%}}\n|}\n{{collapse bottom}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 United States presidential election]]\n* [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries]]\n* [[2020 Republican Party presidential primaries]]\n* [[2020 United States elections]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{United States elections, 2020}}\n\n[[Category:2020 United States presidential election by state|Maine]]\n[[Category:United States presidential elections in Maine|2020]]\n[[Category:2020 Maine elections|Presidential]]\n", "text_old": "{{main|2020 United States presidential election}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 2020 [[United States presidential election]] in Maine\n| country = Maine\n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 2016 United States presidential election in Maine\n| previous_year     = 2016\n| election_date = November 3, 2020\n| next_election     = 2024 United States presidential election in Maine\n| next_year         = 2024\n| turnout = %\n| image_size = \n\n| image1 = Donald Trump official portrait (cropped).jpg\n| nominee1 = [[Donald Trump]]\n| party1 = Republican Party (United States)\n| home_state1 = [[Florida]]\n| running_mate1 = [[Mike Pence]]\n| electoral_vote1 =\n| popular_vote1 = \n| percentage1 = \n\n| image2 = Joe Biden 2013.jpg\n| nominee2 = [[Joe Biden]]\n| party2 = Democratic Party (United States)\n| home_state2 = [[Delaware]]\n| running_mate2 = TBA\n| electoral_vote2 =\n| popular_vote2 = \n| percentage2 = \n\n| title = President\n| before_election = [[Donald Trump]]\n| before_party = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election = TBA\n| after_party = \n}}\n{{ElectionsME}}\nThe '''2020 United States presidential election in Maine''' is scheduled to take place on Tuesday, November 3, 2020, as part of the [[2020 United States elections]] in which all 50 states plus the [[Washington, D.C.|District of Columbia]] will participate.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-elections-key-dates-midterms-2020-presidential-house-congress-senate-a8472821.html|title=US elections key dates: When are the 2018 midterms and the 2020 presidential campaign?|last=Kelly|first=Ben|date=August 13, 2018|work=[[The Independent]]|access-date=January 3, 2019}}</ref> [[Maine]] voters will choose electors to represent them in the [[United States Electoral College|Electoral College]] via a popular vote. The state of Maine has 4 electoral votes in the Electoral College.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.archives.gov/federal-register/electoral-college/allocation.html|title=Distribution of Electoral Votes|website=[[National Archives and Records Administration]]|access-date=January 3, 2019}}</ref> Unlike all other states except [[Nebraska]], Maine awards two electoral votes based on the statewide vote, and one vote for each congressional district.  In [[2016 United States presidential election in Maine|the 2016 election]], Maine split its vote for the first time since [[1828 United States presidential election in Maine|1828]], awarding one electoral vote to [[Donald Trump]] as he got the most votes in [[Maine's 2nd congressional district]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.state.me.us/sos/cec/elec/results/results16-17.html#tally |title=Bureau of Corporations, Elections & Commissions, Elections and Voting, Results, 2014 Tabulations |publisher=State.me.us |date= |accessdate=2017-08-25}}</ref>\n\nMaine will be the first state ever to use [[Ranked-choice voting in the United States|ranked-choice voting]] for the presidential general election, with voters able to rank their preferred candidates on the ballot.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressherald.com/2019/09/06/governor-mills-allows-ranked-choice-voting-in-maines-presidential-elections/|title=Gov. Mills allows ranked-choice voting in Maine\u2019s presidential elections|last=Writer|first=Scott ThistleStaff|date=2019-09-06|website=Press Herald|access-date=2019-09-06}}</ref> Prior to 2019, no other American state thus far has used a voting system other than [[First-past-the-post voting|first-past-the-post]] at the national (presidential) level.\n\n==Primary elections==\nThe primary elections were held on [[Super Tuesday]], March 3, 2020.\n\n===Republican primary===\nIncumbent President [[Donald Trump]] ran unopposed in the Republican primary, and thus he received all of Maine's 22 delegates to the [[2020 Republican National Convention]].<ref name=\"GP-GOP\">{{cite web|title=Maine Republican Delegation 2020|url=https://www.thegreenpapers.com/P20/ME-R|publisher=The Green Papers|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Democratic primary===\nIn an electoral upset, moderate candidate [[Joe Biden]] won the state, which primary opponent [[Bernie Sanders]] previously won in [[2016 Maine Democratic caucuses|2016]].\n{{transcluded section|source=2020 Maine Democratic primary}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h:2020 Maine Democratic primary|Results}}}}\n\n==General election==\n===Predictions===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Source\n!Ranking\n!As of\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[The Cook Political Report]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cookpolitical.com/sites/default/files/2020-03/EC%20030920.4.pdf|title=2020 POTUS Race ratings|website=The Cook Political Report|language=en|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref>\n|{{USRaceRating|Lean|D}}\n|March 9, 2020\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Stuart Rothenberg|Inside Elections]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insideelections.com/ratings/president|title=POTUS Ratings {{!}} Inside Elections|website=insideelections.com|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref>\n|{{USRaceRating|Lean|D}}\n|April 3, 2020\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Sabato's Crystal Ball]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://centerforpolitics.org/crystalball/2020-president/|title=Larry J. Sabato's Crystal Ball \u00bb 2020 President|website=crystalball.centerforpolitics.org|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref>\n|{{USRaceRating|Likely|D}}\n|April 2, 2020\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Politico]]<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.politico.com/2020-election/race-forecasts-and-predictions/president/ |title=2020 Election Forecast|date=November 19, 2019 |publisher=[[Politico]]}}</ref>\n|{{USRaceRating|Lean|D}}\n|November 19, 2019\n|}\n===Polling===\n;with Donald Trump and Joe Biden\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;text-align:center;\"\n|- valign=bottom style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n! Poll source\n! Date(s)<br>administered\n! Sample<br>size{{efn|name=key|Key:<br>A \u2013 all adults<br>RV \u2013 registered voters<br>LV \u2013 likely voters<br>V \u2013 unclear}}\n! Margin<br>{{nowrap|of error}}\n! Donald<br>Trump (R)\n! Joe<br>Biden (D)\n! Undecided\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [https://www.publicpolicypolling.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/MaineResults.pdf Public Policy Polling]\n| March 2\u20133, 2020\n| 872\n| \u00b1&nbsp;3.3%\n| 42%\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}| '''52%'''\n| 6%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [https://www.publicpolicypolling.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/PPP_Release_ME_101519.pdf Public Policy Polling]\n| Oct 11\u201313, 2019\n| 939 (LV)\n| \u00b1&nbsp;3.2%\n| 42%\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}| '''54%'''\n| 4%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [https://www.aarp.org/content/dam/aarp/research/surveys_statistics/politics/2019/five-state-prescription-drug-survey-annotated-questionnaire-ME.doi.10.26419-2Fres.00335.004.pdf Fabrizio Ward/AARP]\n| Jul 29\u201331, 2019\n| 600\n| \u00b1&nbsp;4.0%\n| 44%\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}| '''50%'''\n| 5%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [http://orlando-politics.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Maine-Jun-26-2019.pdf Gravis Marketing]\n| Jun 24, 2019\n| 767\n| \u00b1&nbsp;3.5%\n| 46%\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}| '''54%'''\n| \u2013\n|}\n\n;with Joe Biden in Maine's 1st Congressional District\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;text-align:center;\"\n|- valign=bottom style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n! Poll source\n! Date(s)<br>administered\n! Sample<br>size{{efn|name=key}}\n! Margin<br>{{nowrap|of error}}\n! Donald<br>Trump (R)\n! Joe<br>Biden (D)\n! Undecided\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [https://www.publicpolicypolling.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/PPP_Release_ME_101519.pdf Public Policy Polling]\n| Oct 11\u201313, 2019\n| 478 (LV)\n| \u2013\n| 38%\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}| '''58%'''\n| 3%\n|}\n\n;with Joe Biden in Maine's 2nd Congressional District\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;text-align:center;\"\n|- valign=bottom style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n! Poll source\n! Date(s)<br>administered\n! Sample<br>size{{efn|name=key}}\n! Margin<br>{{nowrap|of error}}\n! Donald<br>Trump (R)\n! Joe<br>Biden (D)\n! Undecided\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [https://www.publicpolicypolling.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/PPP_Release_ME_101519.pdf Public Policy Polling]\n| Oct 11\u201313, 2019\n| 461 (LV)\n| \u2013\n| 46%\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}| '''49%'''\n| 4%\n|}\n\n{{collapse top|1=<span style=\"font-size:88%;\">Former candidates</span>|left=yes|bg=#B0CEFF;line-height:135%;|border=none}}\n;with Donald Trump and Pete Buttigieg\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;text-align:center;\"\n|- valign=bottom style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n! Poll source\n! Date(s)<br>administered\n! Sample<br>size{{efn|name=key}}\n! Margin<br>{{nowrap|of error}}\n! Donald<br>Tru