Book Culture: An Illustrated History|url=https://books.google.com/?id=gW36Qs3rLB0C |year=2000 |publisher=Collectors Press, Inc.|isbn=978-1-888054-38-5 |pages=128\u2013129}}</ref> In 1928, the brothers' partnership ended and Schomburg found work with the [[National Screen Service]], creating [[Magic lantern|lantern slides]] and working on [[Trailer (promotion)|movie trailers]] there through 1944.\n[[File:Alex Schomburg - Harl Vincent - Marvel Science Stories for April-May 1939 - Illustration for Newscast.jpg|Illustration for [[Harl Vincent]]'s ''Newscast'' in ''[[Marvel Science Stories]]'' (May 1939)|thumb|left]]\nDuring the 1930s, in addition to working for the NSS, Schomburg freelanced [[Standard Comics|Better Publications]], producing interior line art for ''Thrilling Wonder Stories'' and others of the company's [[pulp magazine]]s. His skill at drawing anything mechanical soon had him illustrating aviation covers for ''[[Flying Aces (magazine)|Flying Aces]]'' and electronic equipment for the [[Hugo Gernsback]] pulp ''Radio Craft.'' Schomburg's first [[science fiction]]-themed cover was for the September 1939 issue of ''Startling Stories.'' As the artist recalled in 1939, \"One day the publisher asked me to do an illustration for ''Thrilling Wonder Stories''. I had always been interested in science fiction and they liked the way I handled the art work. I enjoy reading the story as much as doing the illustrations. In my opinion an illustration is very important. For instance, give the same story to two different persons ... then ask them to picture a certain scene. You can bet they'll be entirely different.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://archive.org/details/Thrilling_Wonder_Stories_v13n03_1939-06_BetterGorgonRS/page/n87|title=Meet Our Science Fiction Family > Alex Schomburg| work=Thrilling Wonder Stories|volume=13|issue=3|date=June 1939|page=87|publisher=[[Better Publications]]}}</ref>\n\nThe following decade, Schomburg freelanced primarily for [[Timely Comics]], the 1940s forerunner of [[Marvel Comics|Marvel]], displaying his talent for action tableaux in covers featuring [[Captain America]], the [[Namor|Sub-Mariner]], the [[Human Torch]], and other [[superhero]]es. His first recorded comic-book work is two covers released the same month, for ''[[Daring Mystery Comics]]'' #1 and ''[[Marvel Mystery Comics]]'' #3 (both [[cover-date]]d Jan. 1940).<ref name=gcd>[https://www.comics.org/credit/name/Alex%20Schomburg/sort/chrono/ Alex Schomburg] at the [[Grand Comics Database]].</ref><ref name=checklist>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080723114800/http://www.ess.comics.org/ess/schomburg/sccheckl.html \"The Alex Schomburg Checklist] at LiveForEverett.com. Archived from the [http://www.ess.comics.org/ess/schomburg/sccheckl.html original] on July, 23, 2008.</ref> Schomburg would draw most of the companies covers, as well as a smattering of single-page interior illustrations, through ''Marvel Mystery Comics'' #76 (Sept. 1946). He also provided covers for [[Ned Pines|Pines Publications]], for titles including ''Exciting Comics'' and ''[[America's Best Comics#History|America's Best Comics]]'', featuring such superheroes as the [[Black Terror]] and the [[Fighting Yank]], as well as for [[Harvey Comics]], including the licensed radio-series crimefighter star of ''[[Green Hornet|Green Hornet Comics]]''.<ref name=gcd /><ref name=checklist /> On some Pines comics from 1947 to 1949, he signed covers '''\"Xela\"'''.<ref name=gcd-xela>[https://www.comics.org/credit/name/Xela/sort/chrono/ \"Xela\"] at the Grand Comics Database.</ref>\n\nIn the early 1950s, Schomburg left comics and spent the remainder of his career on covers and illustrations for science fiction magazines, astrology publications, and books, including the Winston juvenile series.\n\nIn 1977, Schomburg and a few of his fellow Golden Age comic book artists collaborated on the ''[[Invaders (comics)|Invaders]]'' Annual #1, written by [[Roy Thomas]]. Schomburg penciled and inked a six-page chapter featuring the [[Human Torch (android)|Golden Age Human Torch]].<ref name=gcd />\n\nLate in life, Schomburg resided in [[Hillsboro, Oregon]], and died in [[Beaverton, Oregon]], on April 7, 1998.<ref>{{cite web| title= Alex Schomburg (1905-1998) | url = http://pulpartists.com/Schomburg.html | publisher= PulpArtists.com | first= David|last= Saunders| date= 2009| access-date= March 22, 2015| archivedate= June 21, 2014| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140621025448/http://www.pulpartists.com/Schomburg.html | url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n[[File:Fantastic October 1961 front.jpg|thumb|''Fantastic'' (Oct. 1961). Cover art by Schomburg]]\n* Nominated for [[Hugo Award for Best Professional Artist]] 1962; runner-up\n* Doc Smith Second Stage Lensman Award September 30, 1979 Moscon 1\n* [[Frank R. Paul]] Award 1984\n* [[Inkpot Award]] 1985\n* [[Kentucky colonel]] May 6, 1986\n* [[Chesley Awards|Chesley Award]] (A.S.F.A. Award for Artistic Achievement) 1986\n* [[Science fiction convention#Guests of Honor|Guest of Honor]], [[PulpCon]] 16, July 9\u201312, 1987, Dayton, Ohio\n* [[List of lifetime achievement awards|Lifetime Achievement Award]], Kansas City Comic Con, Fall 1989\n* [[First Fandom Hall of Fame award]] 1990\n* [[47th World Science Fiction Convention]] Noreascon III Special Committee Award (Lifetime Achievement Award), 1989, for contributions to Science Fiction\n* [[List of Eisner Award winners|The Will Eisner Award Hall of Fame]] 1999\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Critical assessments==\n[[Stan Lee]] wrote:\n{{quote|text=I've always felt that Alex Schomburg was to comic books what [[Norman Rockwell]] was to ''[[The Saturday Evening Post]]''. He was totally unique, with an amazing distinctive style. You could never mistake a Schomburg cover for any other artist's. ...&nbsp;I remember hearing [[Timely Comics]] publisher [[Martin Goodman (publisher)|Martin Goodman]] tell me time and again how great a cover illustrator Alex was, and how he wished we had more like him. ...&nbsp;[D]espite the quantity of work we gave him, despite the care and effort that went into every Schomburg cover, I cannot remember Alex ever being late with any illustration.<ref>{{cite web | last = Lee | first= Stan | url = http://www.alexschomburg.com/press_stan_lee.htm |title=Full text written by Stan Lee&nbsp;... about Alex Schomburg | publisher = The Official Estate of Alex Schomburg| access-date= March 22, 2015 | archivedate= February 5, 2015| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150205035232/http://alexschomburg.com/press_stan_lee.htm | url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Puerto Rico|Biography}}\n*[[List of Puerto Ricans]]\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book| editor-last=Gustafson| editor-first= Jon| title=Chroma: The Art of Alex Schomburg| location=Poughkeepsie, New York | publisher=Father Tree Press| date= 1986}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Alex Schomburg}}\n*[http://www.alexschomburg.com/ The Official Estate of Alex Schomburg]. [https://web.archive.org/web/20141216190456/http://alexschomburg.com/ Archived] from the original on December 16, 2014.\n*{{isfdb name|id=Alex_Schomburg}}\n* {{Find a Grave|102279998}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Duin |first=Steve |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060717203731/http://www.ess.comics.org/ess/arscho01.html |archivedate=July 17, 2006 |title=Golden Age Great: Alex Schomburg |journal=Overstreet's Golden Age Quarterly |issue=2 |date=December 1993 |publisher=Reprinted at LiveForEverett.com |url=http://www.ess.comics.org/ess/arscho01.html |url-status=dead}}\n*{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060207021726/http://www.ess.comics.org/ess/schomburg/sccheckl.html| archivedate=February 7, 2006|title=The Alex Schomburg Checklist|url=http://www.ess.comics.org/ess/schomburg/sccheckl.html}}\n* {{LCAuth|n89635394|Alex Schomburg|1|}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schomburg, Alex}}\n[[Category:1905 births]]\n[[Category:1998 deaths]]\n[[Category:American speculative fiction artists]]\n[[Category:American illustrators]]\n[[Category:American comics artists]]\n[[Category:Golden Age comics creators]]\n[[Category:Science fiction artists]]\n[[Category:Will Eisner Award Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics people]]\n[[Category:Pulp fiction artists]]\n", "name_user": "KC Roosters", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changingshort descriptionfrom \"Puerto Rican artist known for book and comics illustration\" to \"Puerto Rican commercial artist and comic-book artist and painter\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alex_Schomburg"}
